<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Grow Lights</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Buying by brightness claims alone:</strong> tray coverage and distance still matter more than the headline marketing.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring how the light fits the tray footprint:</strong> poor fit usually leads to uneven seedlings.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing a fixed setup that cannot move with plant growth:</strong> adjustability is one of the most useful real-world features.</li>
    <li><strong>Assuming all seedlings need the same intensity for the same length of time:</strong> longer indoor starts raise the demand on the setup.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best grow-light choice usually comes from matching the light to the tray system, not from choosing the most technical-looking option.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most home seed starting, buy a simple adjustable grow-light setup that covers standard trays evenly and lets you keep the light close to the seedlings as they grow.
  </p>

  <p>
    Do not overbuy for features if the setup becomes harder to use. Coverage, tray fit, and height adjustment are usually more important than flashy extras. If you start seeds every year, choose a system that is easy to repeat and expand one tray shelf at a time.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best grow light is usually the one that fits your trays well, stays close to the seedlings, and is easy to use consistently.
  </p>
